# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fishers-exact-test
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] In statistics, **Barnard’s test** is an exact test used in the analysis of 2 × 2 contingency tables with one margin fixed.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard’s tests are really a class of hypothesis tests, also known as unconditional exact tests for two independent binomials.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] These tests examine the association of two categorical variables and are often a more powerful alternative than Fisher's exact test for 2 × 2 contingency tables.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard, the test did not gain popularity due to the computational difficulty of calculating the p value and Fisher’s specious disapproval.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Nowadays, even for sample sizes *n* ~ 1 million, computers can often implement Barnard’s test in a few seconds or less.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard’s test is used to test the independence of rows and columns in a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] The test assumes each response is independent.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Under independence, there are three types of study designs that yield a 2 × 2 table, and Barnard's test applies to the second type.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] To distinguish the different types of designs, suppose a researcher is interested in testing whether a novel treatment quickly heals an infection.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Another possible study design would be to give 50 infected subjects the novel treatment, 50 infected subjects the standard treatment, and see if the infection is still present after a set time.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] This type of design is common in clinical trials.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] The final possible study design would be to give 50 infected subjects the novel treatment, 50 infected subjects the standard treatment, and stop the experiment once a pre-determined number of subjects has healed from the infection.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] This type of design is rare, but has the same structure as the *lady tasting tea* study that led R.A.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] The second study design is given by the product of two independent binomial distributions; the totals in one of the margins (either the row totals or the column totals) are constrained by the experimental design, but the totals in other margin are free.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] The third design is given by the hypergeometric distribution; where both the total numbers in each column and row are constrained.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] For example an individual is allowed to taste 8 cups of soda, but must assign four to each category "brand X" and "brand Y", so that both the row totals and the column totals are constrained to four.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] The operational difference between Barnard’s exact test and Fisher’s exact test is how they handle the nuisance parameter(s) of the common success probability, when calculating the p value.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Fisher's exact test avoids estimating the nuisance parameter(s) by conditioning on both margins, an approximately ancillary statistic that constrains the possible outcomes.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] The problem with that Fisher's procedure is that it excludes some of the outcomes which are possibilities when there is no constraint on the total numbers in each column and row.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard’s test considers all legitimate possible values of the nuisance parameter(s) and chooses the value(s) that maximizes the p value.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] However, even when the data come from double-binomial distribution, the conditioning (that leads to using the hypergeometric distribution for calculating the Fisher's exact p value) produces a valid test, if one accepts that Fisher's test will necessarily miss some positive results.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard's test is not biased in this way, and is more suitable for a broader range of experiment types, including those which are most common, in which there is no experimental constraint on one of either the row sum or the column sum of the table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Both tests bound the type I error rate at the α level, and hence are technically 'valid'.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] In fact, a variant of Barnard’s test, called Boschloo's test, is uniformly more powerful than Fisher’s test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard’s test has been used alongside Fisher's exact test in project management research.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard's tests are not appropriate in the rare case of an experimental design that constrains both marginal results (e.g. ‘taste tests’); although rare, experimentally imposed constraints on both marginal totals make the true sampling distribution for the table hypergeometric.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] Barnard's test can be applied to larger tables, but the computation time increases and the power advantage quickly decreases.
[src:fishers-exact-test/barnard-s-test] It remains unclear which test statistic is preferred when implementing Barnard's test; however, most test statistics yield uniformly more powerful tests than Fisher's exact test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] A **chi-squared test** (also **chi-square** or **χ2 test**) is a statistical hypothesis test used in the analysis of contingency tables when the sample sizes are large.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In simpler terms, this test is primarily used to examine whether two categorical variables (*two dimensions of the contingency table*) are independent in influencing the test statistic (*values within the table*).
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The test is valid when the test statistic is chi-squared distributed under the null hypothesis, specifically Pearson's chi-squared test and variants thereof.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Pearson's chi-squared test is used to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference between the expected frequencies and the observed frequencies in one or more categories of a contingency table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] For contingency tables with smaller sample sizes, a Fisher's exact test is used instead.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In the standard applications of this test, the observations are classified into mutually exclusive classes.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] If the null hypothesis that there are no differences between the classes in the population is true, the test statistic computed from the observations follows a χ2 frequency distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The purpose of the test is to evaluate how likely the observed frequencies would be assuming the null hypothesis is true.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Test statistics that follow a χ2 distribution occur when the observations are independent.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] There are also χ2 tests for testing the null hypothesis of independence of a pair of random variables based on observations of the pairs.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] At the end of the 19th century, Pearson noticed the existence of significant skewness within some biological observations.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In 1900, Pearson published a paper on the χ2 test which is considered to be one of the foundations of modern statistics.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In this paper, Pearson investigated a test of goodness of fit.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Suppose that n observations in a random sample from a population are classified into k mutually exclusive classes with respective observed numbers of observations xi (for *i* = 1,2,…,*k*), and a null hypothesis gives the probability pi that an observation falls into the ith class.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Pearson proposed that, under the circumstance of the null hypothesis being correct, as *n* → ∞ the limiting distribution of the quantity given below is the χ2 distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] will usually be positive and small enough to be omitted.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In a conclusion, Pearson argued that if we regarded *X*′2 as also distributed as χ2 distribution with *k* − 1 degrees of freedom, the error in this approximation would not affect practical decisions.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] This conclusion caused some controversy in practical applications and was not settled for 20 years until Fisher's 1922 and 1924 papers.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] One test statistic that follows a chi-squared distribution exactly is the test that the variance of a normally distributed population has a given value based on a sample variance.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Such tests are uncommon in practice because the true variance of the population is usually unknown.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] For an exact test used in place of the 2 × 2 chi-squared test for independence when all the row and column totals were fixed by design, see Fisher's exact test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] When the row or column margins (or both) are random variables (as in most common research designs) this tends to be overly conservative and underpowered.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] For an exact test used in place of the 2 × 1 chi-squared test for goodness of fit, see binomial test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Using the chi-squared distribution to interpret Pearson's chi-squared statistic requires one to assume that the discrete probability of observed binomial frequencies in the table can be approximated by the continuous chi-squared distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] This assumption is not quite correct and introduces some error.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] To reduce the error in approximation, Frank Yates suggested a correction for continuity that adjusts the formula for Pearson's chi-squared test by subtracting 0.5 from the absolute difference between each observed value and its expected value in a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] This reduces the chi-squared value obtained and thus increases its *p*-value.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] If a sample of size *n* is taken from a population having a normal distribution, then there is a result (see distribution of the sample variance) which allows a test to be made of whether the variance of the population has a pre-determined value.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] For example, a manufacturing process might have been in stable condition for a long period, allowing a value for the variance to be determined essentially without error.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Suppose that a variant of the process is being tested, giving rise to a small sample of *n* product items whose variation is to be tested.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The test statistic *T* in this instance could be set to be the sum of squares about the sample mean, divided by the nominal value for the variance (i.e. the value to be tested as holding).
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Then *T* has a chi-squared distribution with *n* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] For example, if the sample size is 21, the acceptance region for *T* with a significance level of 5% is between 9.59 and 34.17.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Suppose there is a city of 1,000,000 residents with four neighborhoods: *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D*.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] A random sample of 650 residents of the city is taken and their occupation is recorded as "white collar", "blue collar", or "no collar".
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The null hypothesis is that each person's neighborhood of residence is independent of the person's occupational classification.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Let us take the sample living in neighborhood *A*, 150, to estimate what proportion of the whole 1,000,000 live in neighborhood *A*.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Similarly we take ⁠349/650⁠ to estimate what proportion of the 1,000,000 are white-collar workers.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The sum of these quantities over all of the cells is the test statistic; in this case, $\approx 24.57$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] If the test statistic is improbably large according to that chi-squared distribution, then one rejects the null hypothesis of independence.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] A related issue is a test of homogeneity.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Suppose that instead of giving every resident of each of the four neighborhoods an equal chance of inclusion in the sample, we decide in advance how many residents of each neighborhood to include.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Then each resident has the same chance of being chosen as do all residents of the same neighborhood, but residents of different neighborhoods would have different probabilities of being chosen if the four sample sizes are not proportional to the populations of the four neighborhoods.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In such a case, we would be testing "homogeneity" rather than "independence".
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The question is whether the proportions of blue-collar, white-collar, and no-collar workers in the four neighborhoods are the same.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] However, the test is done in the same way.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In cryptanalysis, the chi-squared test is used to compare the distribution of plaintext and (possibly) decrypted ciphertext.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The lowest value of the test means that the decryption was successful with high probability.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] This method can be generalized for solving modern cryptographic problems.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In bioinformatics, the chi-squared test is used to compare the distribution of certain properties of genes (e.g., genomic content, mutation rate, interaction network clustering, etc.) belonging to different categories (e.g., disease genes, essential genes, genes on a certain chromosome etc.).
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] The chi-squared test, while widely used for categorical data analysis, has several important limitations that researchers should consider.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] First, it assumes that observations are independent; violating this assumption can lead to misleading results.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Second, the test is sensitive to sample size.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] In very large samples, even trivial differences between observed and expected frequencies may produce statistically significant results, while in very small samples, the test may lack power to detect meaningful associations.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Third, the chi-squared test does not measure the strength or practical importance of an association—it only indicates whether a significant relationship exists.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Effect size measures, such as Cramér's V or the contingency coefficient, should be reported alongside the test statistic to provide context.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Finally, the test may be inaccurate when expected frequencies in any cell are very small, often recommended to be at least 5; in such cases, exact tests or alternative methods are preferred.
[src:fishers-exact-test/chi-squared-test] Researchers must also be cautious when dealing with unevenly distributed categories, as dominant groups can overshadow patterns in smaller groups.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] In statistics, a **contingency table** (also known as a **cross tabulation** or **crosstab**) is a type of table in a matrix format that displays the multivariate frequency distribution of the variables.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] They are heavily used in survey research, business intelligence, engineering, and scientific research.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] They provide a basic picture of the interrelation between two variables and can help find interactions between them.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The term *contingency table* was first used by Karl Pearson in "On the Theory of Contingency and Its Relation to Association and Normal Correlation", part of the *Drapers' Company Research Memoirs Biometric Series I* published in 1904.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] A crucial problem of multivariate statistics is finding the (direct-)dependence structure underlying the variables contained in high-dimensional contingency tables.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] If some of the conditional independences are revealed, then even the storage of the data can be done in a smarter way (see Lauritzen (2002)).
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] In order to do this one can use information theory concepts, which gain the information only from the distribution of probability, which can be expressed easily from the contingency table by the relative frequencies.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] A pivot table is a way to create contingency tables using spreadsheet software.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Suppose there are two variables, sex (male or female) and handedness (right- or left-handed).
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Further suppose that 100 individuals are randomly sampled from a very large population as part of a study of sex differences in handedness.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] A contingency table can be created to display the numbers of individuals who are male right-handed and left-handed, female right-handed and left-handed.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Such a contingency table is shown below.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The numbers of the males, females, and right- and left-handed individuals are called marginal totals.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The grand total (the total number of individuals represented in the contingency table) is the number in the bottom right corner.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The table allows users to see at a glance that the proportion of men who are right-handed is about the same as the proportion of women who are right-handed although the proportions are not identical.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The strength of the association can be measured by the odds ratio, and the population odds ratio estimated by the sample odds ratio.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] If the proportions of individuals in the different columns vary significantly between rows (or vice versa), it is said that there is a *contingency* between the two variables.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] In other words, the two variables are *not* independent.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] If there is no contingency, it is said that the two variables are *independent*.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The example above is the simplest kind of contingency table, a table in which each variable has only two levels; this is called a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] In principle, any number of rows and columns may be used.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] There may also be more than two variables, but higher order contingency tables are difficult to represent visually.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The relation between ordinal variables, or between ordinal and categorical variables, may also be represented in contingency tables, although such a practice is rare.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] For more on the use of a contingency table for the relation between two ordinal variables, see Goodman and Kruskal's gamma.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The degree of association between the two variables can be assessed by a number of coefficients.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The following subsections describe a few of them.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] For a more complete discussion of their uses, see the main articles linked under each subsection heading.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The simplest measure of association for a 2 × 2 contingency table is the odds ratio.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Given two events, A and B, the odds ratio is defined as the ratio of the odds of A in the presence of B and the odds of A in the absence of B, or equivalently (due to symmetry), the ratio of the odds of B in the presence of A and the odds of B in the absence of A.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Two events are independent if and only if the odds ratio is 1; if the odds ratio is greater than 1, the events are positively associated; if the odds ratio is less than 1, the events are negatively associated.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Then its sign equals the sign of the product of the main diagonal elements of the table minus the product of the off–diagonal elements. φ takes on the minimum value −1.0 or the maximum value of +1.0 if and only if every marginal proportion is equal to 0.5 (and two diagonal cells are empty).
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Two alternatives are the *contingency coefficient* *C*, and Cramér's V.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Another choice is the tetrachoric correlation coefficient but it is only applicable to 2 × 2 tables.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Polychoric correlation is an extension of the tetrachoric correlation to tables involving variables with more than two levels.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Tetrachoric correlation assumes that the variable underlying each dichotomous measure is normally distributed.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The tetrachoric correlation coefficient should not be confused with the Pearson correlation coefficient computed by assigning, say, values 0.0 and 1.0 to represent the two levels of each variable (which is mathematically equivalent to the φ coefficient).
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The lambda coefficient is a measure of the strength of association of the cross tabulations when the variables are measured at the nominal level.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Values range from 0.0 (no association) to 1.0 (the maximum possible association).
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Asymmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement in predicting the dependent variable.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Symmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement when prediction is done in both directions.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] The uncertainty coefficient, or Theil's U, is another measure for variables at the nominal level.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Its values range from −1.0 (100% negative association, or perfect inversion) to +1.0 (100% positive association, or perfect agreement).
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] A value of 0.0 indicates the absence of association.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] This asymmetrical property can lead to insights not as evident in symmetrical measures of association.
[src:fishers-exact-test/contingency-table] Gamma, Tau-b and Tau-c are used when the categories or levels of both variables have a natural order.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] An **exact (significance) test** is a statistical test such that if the null hypothesis is true, then all assumptions made during the derivation of the distribution of the test statistic are met.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Using an exact test provides a significance test that maintains the type I error rate of the test ( $\alpha$ ) at the desired significance level of the test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] For example, an exact test at a significance level of $\alpha =5\%$ , when repeated over many samples where the null hypothesis is true, will reject at most $5\%$ of the time.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] This is in contrast to an *approximate test* in which the desired type I error rate is only approximately maintained (i.e.: the test might reject > 5% of the time), while this approximation may be made as close to $\alpha$ as desired by making the sample size sufficiently large.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Exact tests that are based on discrete test statistics may be conservative, indicating that the actual rejection rate lies below the nominal significance level $\alpha$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] As an example, this is the case for Fisher's exact test and its more powerful alternative, Boschloo's test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] If the test statistic is continuous, it will reach the significance level exactly.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Parametric tests, such as those used in exact statistics, are exact tests when the parametric assumptions are fully met, but in practice, the use of the term *exact* (significance) *test* is reserved for non-parametric tests, i.e., tests that do not rest on parametric assumptions.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] However, in practice, most implementations of non-parametric test software use asymptotical algorithms to obtain the significance value, which renders the test non-exact.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Hence, when a result of statistical analysis is termed an “exact test” or specifies an “exact p-value”, this implies that the test is defined without parametric assumptions and is evaluated without making use of approximate algorithms.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] In principle, however, this could also signify that a parametric test has been employed in a situation where all parametric assumptions are fully met, but it is in most cases impossible to prove this completely in a real-world situation.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Exceptions in which it is certain that parametric tests are exact include tests based on the binomial or Poisson distributions.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] The term permutation test is sometimes used as a synonym for exact test, but it should be kept in mind that all permutation tests are exact tests, but not all exact tests are permutation tests.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] and where the sum ranges over all outcomes **y** (including the observed one) that have the same value of the test statistic obtained for the observed sample **x**, or a larger one.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] A simple example of this concept involves the observation that Pearson's chi-squared test is an approximate test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Suppose Pearson's chi-squared test is used to ascertain whether a six-sided die is "fair", indicating that it renders each of the six possible outcomes equally often.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] If the die is thrown *n* times, then one "expects" to see each outcome *n*/6 times.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] where *X**k* is the number of times outcome *k* is observed.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] If the null hypothesis of "fairness" is true, then the probability distribution of the test statistic can be made as close as desired to the chi-squared distribution with 5 degrees of freedom by making the sample size *n* sufficiently large.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] On the other hand, if *n* is small, then the probabilities based on chi-squared distributions may not be sufficiently close approximations.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Finding the exact probability that this test statistic exceeds a certain value would then require a combinatorial enumeration of all outcomes of the experiment that gives rise to such a large value of the test statistic.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] It is then questionable whether the same test statistic ought to be used.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] A likelihood-ratio test might be preferred, and the test statistic might not be a monotone function of the one above.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Fisher's exact test, based on the work of Ronald Fisher and E.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] Pitman in the 1930s, is exact because the sampling distribution (conditional on the marginals) is known exactly.
[src:fishers-exact-test/exact-test] This should be compared with Pearson's chi-squared test, which (although it tests the same null) is not exact because the distribution of the test statistic is only asymptotically correct.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The test is named after its inventor, Ronald Fisher, who is said to have devised the test following a comment from Muriel Bristol, who claimed to be able to detect whether the tea or the milk was added first to her cup.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] He tested her claim in the "lady tasting tea" experiment.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The test is useful for categorical data that result from classifying objects in two different ways; it is used to examine the significance of the association (contingency) between the two kinds of classification.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] So in Fisher's original example, one criterion of classification could be whether milk or tea was put in the cup first; the other could be whether Bristol thinks that the milk or tea was put in first.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] We want to know whether these two classifications are associated—that is, whether Bristol really can tell whether milk or tea was poured in first.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Most uses of the Fisher test involve, like this example, a 2 × 2 contingency table (discussed below).
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The *p*-value from the test is computed as if the margins of the table are fixed, i.e. as if, in the tea-tasting example, Bristol knows the number of cups with each treatment (milk or tea first) and will therefore provide guesses with the correct number in each category.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] As pointed out by Fisher, this leads under a null hypothesis of independence to a hypergeometric distribution of the numbers in the cells of the table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] This setting is however rare in scientific practice and the test is conservative, when one or both margins are random variables themselves.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] With large samples, a chi-squared test (or better yet, a G-test) can be used in this situation.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] However, the significance value it provides is only an approximation, because the sampling distribution of the test statistic that is calculated is only approximately equal to the theoretical chi-squared distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The approximation is poor when sample sizes are small, or the data are very unequally distributed among the cells of the table, resulting in the cell counts predicted on the null hypothesis (the "expected values") being low.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] In fact, for small, sparse, or unbalanced data, the exact and asymptotic *p*-values can be quite different and may lead to opposite conclusions concerning the hypothesis of interest.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] In contrast the Fisher exact test is, as its name states, exact as long as the experimental procedure keeps the row and column totals fixed, and it can therefore be used regardless of the sample characteristics.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] It becomes difficult to calculate with large samples or well-balanced tables, but fortunately these are exactly the conditions where the chi-squared test is appropriate.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For hand calculations, the test is feasible only in the case of a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] However the principle of the test can be extended to the general case of an *m* × *n* table, and some statistical packages provide a calculation (sometimes using a Monte Carlo method to obtain an approximation) for the more general case.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The test can also be used to quantify the *overlap* between two sets.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For example, in enrichment analyses in statistical genetics one set of genes may be annotated for a given phenotype and the user may be interested in testing the overlap of their own set with those.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The test assumes genes in either list are taken from a broader set of genes (e.g. all remaining genes).
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] A *p*-value may then be calculated, summarizing the significance of the overlap between the two lists.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] We set up the following probability model underlying Fisher's exact test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Suppose we have ${\textstyle a+b}$ blue balls, and ${\textstyle c+d}$ red balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] We throw them together into a black box, shake well, then remove them one by one until we have pulled out exactly ${\textstyle a+c}$ balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] We call these balls "class I" and the ${\textstyle b+d}$ remaining balls "class II".
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The question is to calculate the probability that exactly ${\textstyle a}$ blue balls are in class I.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Every other entry in the table is fixed once we fill in one entry of the table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Suppose we pretend that every ball is labelled, and before we start pulling out the balls, we permutate them uniformly randomly, then pull out the first ${\textstyle a+c}$ balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] This gives us ${\textstyle n!}$ possibilities.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Of these possibilities, we condition on the case where the first ${\textstyle a+c}$ balls contain exactly ${\textstyle a}$ blue balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The two selected sets would be filled with blue balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The rest would be filled with red balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Once we have selected the sets, we can populate them with an arbitrary ordering of the ${\textstyle a+b}$ blue balls.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] This gives us ${\textstyle (a+b)!}$ possibilities.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Same for the red balls, with ${\textstyle (c+d)!}$ possibilities.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Suppose each blue ball and red ball has an equal and independent probability ${\textstyle p}$ of being in class I, and ${\textstyle 1-p}$ of being in class II.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Then the number of class-I blue balls is binomially distributed.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The probability there are exactly ${\textstyle a}$ of them is ${\textstyle {\binom {a+b}{a}}p^{a}(1-p)^{b}}$ , and the probability there are exactly ${\textstyle c}$ of red class I balls is ${\textstyle {\binom {c+d}{c}}p^{c}(1-p)^{d}}$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The probability that there are precisely ${\textstyle a+c}$ of class I balls, regardless of number of red or blue balls in it, is ${\textstyle {\binom {n}{a+c}}p^{a+c}(1-p)^{b+d}}$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For example, a sample of teenagers might be divided into male and female on one hand and those who are and are not currently studying for a statistics exam on the other.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For example, we hypothesize that the proportion of studying students is higher among the women than among the men, and we want to test whether any difference in proportions that we observe is significant.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] If we were to choose 10 of the teenagers at random, what is the probability that 9 or more of them would be among the 12 women and only 1 or fewer from among the 12 men?
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Before we proceed with the Fisher test, we first introduce some notations.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] We represent the cells by the letters *a, b, c* and *d*, call the totals across rows and columns *marginal totals*, and represent the grand total by *n*.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Fisher showed that conditional on the margins of the table, *a* is distributed as a hypergeometric distribution with *a+c* draws from a population with *a+b* successes and *c+d* failures.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] where ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is the binomial coefficient and the symbol ! indicates the factorial operator.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] If the marginal totals (i.e. $a+b$ , $c+d$ , $a+c$ , and $b+d$ ) are known, only a single degree of freedom is left: the value e.g. of a suffices to deduce the other values.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Now, $p=p(a)$ is the probability that a elements are positive in a random selection (without replacement) of $a+c$ elements from a larger set containing n elements in total out of which $a+b$ are positive, which is precisely the definition of the hypergeometric distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The formula above gives the exact hypergeometric probability of observing this particular arrangement of the data, assuming the given marginal totals, on the null hypothesis that men and women are equally likely to be studiers.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] This remains true even if men enter our sample with different probabilities than women.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The requirement is merely that the two classification characteristics—gender, and studier (or not)—are not associated.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Then still, were we to calculate the distribution of cell entries conditional given marginals, we would obtain the above formula in which neither ${\mathfrak {p}}$ nor P occurs.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] (Barnard's test relaxes this constraint on one set of the marginal totals.) In the example, there are 11 such cases.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] In order to calculate the significance of the observed data, i.e. the total probability of observing data as extreme or more extreme if the null hypothesis is true, we have to calculate the values of *p* for both these tables, and add them together.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] This value can be interpreted as the sum of evidence provided by the observed data—or any more extreme table—for the null hypothesis (that there is no difference in the proportions of studiers between men and women).
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The smaller the value of *p*, the greater the evidence for rejecting the null hypothesis; so here the evidence is strong that men and women are not equally likely to be studiers.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For a two-tailed test we must also consider tables that are equally extreme, but in the opposite direction.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Unfortunately, classification of the tables according to whether or not they are 'as extreme' is problematic.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] An approach used by the `fisher.test` function in R is to compute the *p*-value by summing the probabilities for all tables with probabilities less than or equal to that of the observed table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] In the example here, the 2-sided *p*-value is twice the 1-sided value—but in general these can differ substantially for tables with small counts, unlike the case with test statistics that have a symmetric sampling distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Fisher's exact test is a standard tool in genomics for identifying statistically under- or over-represented sets of genes.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For example, sets of differentially expressed genes can be tested for significant overlap with predefined functional categories such as Gene Ontology terms, providing insight into biological processes that may be implicated in an experiment.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] In text analytics, Fisher's exact test has been used to quantify whether a given word is statistically associated with a particular document within a corpus.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The negative logarithm of the resulting *p*-value has been shown to be closely related to the TF–IDF term-weighting scheme from information retrieval.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Fisher's test gives exact *p*-values, but some authors have argued that it is conservative, i.e. that its actual rejection rate is below the nominal significance level.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The apparent contradiction stems from the combination of a discrete statistic with fixed significance levels.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Consider the following proposal for a significance test at the 5%-level: reject the null hypothesis for each table to which Fisher's test assigns a *p*-value equal to or smaller than 5%.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Because the set of all tables is discrete, there may not be a table for which equality is achieved.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] If $\alpha _{e}$ is the largest *p*-value smaller than 5% which can actually occur for some table, then the proposed test effectively tests at the $\alpha _{e}$ -level.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For small sample sizes, $\alpha _{e}$ might be significantly lower than 5%.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] While this effect occurs for any discrete statistic (not just in contingency tables, or for Fisher's test), it has been argued that the problem is compounded by the fact that Fisher's test conditions on the marginals.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] To avoid the problem, many authors discourage the use of fixed significance levels when dealing with discrete problems.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The decision to condition on the margins of the table is also controversial.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The *p*-values derived from Fisher's test come from the distribution that conditions on the margin totals.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] In this sense, the test is exact only for the conditional distribution and not the original table where the margin totals may change from experiment to experiment.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] It is possible to obtain an exact *p*-value for the 2×2 table when the margins are not held fixed.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Barnard's test, for example, allows for random margins.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] However, some authors (including, later, Barnard himself) have criticized Barnard's test based on this property.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] They argue that the marginal success total is an (almost) ancillary statistic, containing (almost) no information about the tested property.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The act of conditioning on the marginal success rate from a 2×2 table can be shown to ignore some information in the data about the unknown odds ratio.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The argument that the marginal totals are (almost) ancillary implies that the appropriate likelihood function for making inferences about this odds ratio should be conditioned on the marginal success rate.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Whether this lost information is important for inferential purposes is the essence of the controversy.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] An alternative exact test, Barnard's exact test, has been developed and proponents of it suggest that this method is more powerful, particularly in 2×2 tables.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Furthermore, Boschloo's test is an exact test that is uniformly more powerful than Fisher's exact test by construction.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Most modern statistical packages will calculate the significance of Fisher tests, in some cases even where the chi-squared approximation would also be acceptable.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] The actual computations as performed by statistical software packages will as a rule differ from those described above, because numerical difficulties may result from the large values taken by the factorials.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] A simple, somewhat better computational approach relies on a gamma function or log-gamma function, but methods for accurate computation of hypergeometric and binomial probabilities remains an active research area.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] For stratified categorical data the Cochran–Mantel–Haenszel test must be used instead of Fisher's test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] Choi et al. propose a *p*-value derived from the likelihood ratio test based on the conditional distribution of the odds ratio given the marginal success rate.
[src:fishers-exact-test/fisher-s-exact-test] This *p*-value is inferentially consistent with classical tests of normally distributed data as well as with likelihood ratios and support intervals based on this conditional likelihood function.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In contrast, the binomial distribution describes the probability of k successes in n draws *with* replacement.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The pmf is positive when $\max(0,n+K-N)\leq k\leq \min(K,n)$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] A random variable distributed hypergeometrically with parameters N , K and n is written ${\textstyle X\sim \operatorname {Hypergeometric} (N,K,n)}$ and has probability mass function ${\textstyle p_{X}(k)}$ above.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] which essentially follows from Vandermonde's identity from combinatorics.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] This identity can be shown by expressing the binomial coefficients in terms of factorials and rearranging the latter.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Additionally, it follows from the symmetry of the problem, described in two different but interchangeable ways.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] For example, consider two rounds of drawing without replacement.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In the first round, K out of N neutral marbles are drawn from an urn without replacement and coloured green.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In the second round, n marbles are drawn without replacement and colored red.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Then, the number of marbles with both colors on them (that is, the number of marbles that have been drawn twice) has the hypergeometric distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The symmetry in K and n stems from the fact that the two rounds are independent, and one could have started by drawing n balls and colouring them red first.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The classical application of the hypergeometric distribution is **sampling without replacement**.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Think of an urn with two colors of marbles, red and green.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Define drawing a green marble as a success and drawing a red marble as a failure.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Let *N* describe the number of **all marbles in the urn** (see contingency table below) and *K* describe the number of **green marbles**, then *N* − *K* corresponds to the number of **red marbles**.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Now, standing next to the urn, you close your eyes and draw n marbles without replacement.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Define *X* as a random variable whose outcome is *k*, the number of green marbles drawn in the experiment.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Indeed, we are interested in calculating the probability of drawing k green marbles in n draws, given that there are K green marbles out of a total of N marbles.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] For this example, assume that there are **5** green and **45** red marbles in the urn.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Standing next to the urn, you close your eyes and draw **10** marbles without replacement.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] What is the probability that exactly **4** of the **10** are green?
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] 2. right hand side - alternatively, drawing all N marbles out of the urn.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Intuitively we would expect it to be even more unlikely that all 5 green marbles will be among the 10 drawn.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] As expected, the probability of drawing 5 green marbles is roughly 35 times less likely than that of drawing 4.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] These symmetries generate the dihedral group $D_{4}$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The probability of drawing any set of green and red marbles (the hypergeometric distribution) depends only on the numbers of green and red marbles, not on the order in which they appear; i.e., it is an exchangeable distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] This is an *ex ante* probability—that is, it is based on not knowing the results of the previous draws.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Let $X\sim \operatorname {Hypergeometric} (N,K,n)$ and $p=K/N$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] is the Kullback–Leibler divergence and it is used that $D(a\parallel b)\geq 2(a-b)^{2}$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The **hypergeometric test** uses the hypergeometric distribution to measure the statistical significance of having drawn a sample consisting of a specific number of k successes (out of n total draws) from a population of size N containing K successes.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In a test for over-representation of successes in the sample, the hypergeometric p-value is calculated as the probability of randomly drawing k or more successes from the population in n total draws.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In a test for under-representation, the p-value is the probability of randomly drawing k or fewer successes.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The test based on the hypergeometric distribution (hypergeometric test) is identical to the corresponding one-tailed version of Fisher's exact test.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Reciprocally, the p-value of a two-sided Fisher's exact test can be calculated as the sum of two appropriate hypergeometric tests (for more information see).
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The test is often used to identify which sub-populations are over- or under-represented in a sample.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] This test has a wide range of applications.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] For example, a marketing group could use the test to understand their customer base by testing a set of known customers for over-representation of various demographic subgroups (e.g., women, people under 30).
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The model of an urn with green and red marbles can be extended to the case where there are more than two colors of marbles.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] This has the same relationship to the multinomial distribution that the hypergeometric distribution has to the binomial distribution—the multinomial distribution is the "with-replacement" distribution and the multivariate hypergeometric is the "without-replacement" distribution.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The properties of this distribution are given in the adjacent table, where *c* is the number of different colors and $N=\sum _{i=1}^{c}K_{i}$ is the total number of marbles in the urn.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Suppose there are 5 black, 10 white, and 15 red marbles in an urn.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Election audits typically test a sample of machine-counted precincts to see if recounts by hand or machine match the original counts.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Mismatches result in either a report or a larger recount.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The sampling rates are usually defined by law, not statistical design, so for a legally defined sample size n, what is the probability of missing a problem which is present in K precincts, such as a hack or bug?
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Bugs are often obscure, and a hacker can minimize detection by affecting only a few precincts, which will still affect close elections, so a plausible scenario is for K to be on the order of 5% of N.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Audits typically cover 1% to 10% of precincts (often 3%), so they have a high chance of missing a problem.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In hold'em poker players make the best hand they can combining the two cards in their hand with the 5 cards (community cards) eventually turned up on the table.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The deck has 52 and there are 13 of each suit.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] For this example assume a player has 2 clubs in the hand and there are 3 cards showing on the table, 2 of which are also clubs.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The player would like to know the probability of one of the next 2 cards to be shown being a club to complete the flush.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] (Note that the probability calculated in this example assumes no information is known about the cards in the other players' hands; however, experienced poker players may consider how the other players place their bets (check, call, raise, or fold) in considering the probability for each scenario.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] There are 4 clubs showing so there are 9 clubs still unseen.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] There are 5 cards showing (2 in the hand and 3 on the table) so there are $52-5=47$ still unseen.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The probability that exactly one of the next two cards turned is a club can be calculated using hypergeometric with $k=1,n=2,K=9$ and $N=47$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The probability that both of the next two cards turned are clubs can be calculated using hypergeometric with $k=2,n=2,K=9$ and $N=47$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The probability that neither of the next two cards turned are clubs can be calculated using hypergeometric with $k=0,n=2,K=9$ and $N=47$ .
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The hypergeometric distribution is indispensable for calculating Keno odds.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] In Keno, 20 balls are randomly drawn from a collection of 80 numbered balls in a container, rather like American Bingo.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Prior to each draw, a player selects a certain number of *spots* by marking a paper form supplied for this purpose.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] For example, a player might *play a 6-spot* by marking 6 numbers, each from a range of 1 through 80 inclusive.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Then (after all players have taken their forms to a cashier and been given a duplicate of their marked form, and paid their wager) 20 balls are drawn.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Some of the balls drawn may match some or all of the balls selected by the player.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Generally speaking, the more *hits* (balls drawn that match player numbers selected) the greater the payoff.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] For example, if a customer bets ("plays") $1 for a 6-spot (not an uncommon example) and hits 4 out of the 6, the casino would pay out $4.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Payouts can vary from one casino to the next, but $4 is a typical value here.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Similarly, the chance for hitting 5 spots out of 6 selected is ${{{6 \choose 5}{{74} \choose {15}}} \over {80 \choose 20}}\approx 0.003095639$ while a typical payout might be $88.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] The only other nonzero payout might be $1 for hitting 3 numbers (i.e., you get your bet back), which has a probability near 0.129819548.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Taking the sum of products of payouts times corresponding probabilities we get an expected return of 0.70986492 or roughly 71% for a 6-spot, for a house advantage of 29%.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] Other spots-played have a similar expected return.
[src:fishers-exact-test/hypergeometric-distribution] This very poor return (for the player) is usually explained by the large overhead (floor space, equipment, personnel) required for the game.
